node.text:
Some of you may have seen I’ve been posting a lot on IG stories this past week about the events surrounding George Floyd’s murder. I’ve wanted to share a video to my normal feed as well that focused on the overall message of #blacklivesmatter and show the unity, community and compassion amongst those protesting police brutality- it’s being overlooked far too much in mainstream media right now. In the same vein, I didn’t want to downplay the severity of what we’re all angry about, or cover up the ugly reality of what a lot of these protests come to look like due to police abuse. 
Sadly, I came across this video today which perfectly encompasses both. I’ve never felt both so much hope for humanity, and such hopelessness for humanity- all in a two minute span. Please watch the entire thing.

Black lives deserve to be heard, and protected. They deserve to have their allies stand beside them and say enough is enough, and we all deserve to protest police brutality without facing that very thing. I’m afraid for the state of the world, but I hope the message of this man is what ultimately prevails. That will only happen if we all stand up to these injustices- it will never happen with silence. ✊🏾✊🏻✊🏿

node.text: We went out into the middle of nowhere for our 2 year anniversary this past week & I had to document how this man is aging like a fine tub of scab blood. It still baffles me how I am fortunate enough to get to know the real you, and that you’re even better than anyone could imagine. Which is saying a lot, because you’re already so rightfully loved. Glad you were born approximately 1 million years ago today, old man. Happy birthday ❤️ @anthonypadilla

node.text: Taking time away from work to focus on my physical and mental health has really taught me how crucial relationships are to our well-being. The friends I’ve grown close to or closer with in the last year have been more of a backbone to my healing than most of them could ever fully know. @loeybug being a shining example of that. This woman has a heart of gold and I’m so lucky to have her in my life. Thanks for the date, Van Loey 💙💛💜💓🧡 Tag a friend who you wanna say something all gushy and cute to in the comments

node.text:
You already KNOW I am an M.Night Shyamalam stan. As a girl growing up in Philly who loved all things horror, twists and turns, and who wanted to someday make my own films, M.Night’s movies have always been a huge inspiration to me and a real comfort seeing them set in my hometown. I am SO thrilled to be partnering with Universal today to talk about his BRAND NEW film, #OldTheMovie.  Your time is running out… but you’re not gunna wanna miss this, so keep reading to enter this special giveaway 👇🏻👀

The tide’s coming in. 

⏳
 
Hey LA! Check out this hourglass at the Santa Monica Pier and enter for a chance to win the trip of a lifetime. Get tickets now to see #OldTheMovie at http://www.fandango.com/old … and if you visit the Hourglass say the code words: “TIME IS TICKING” to the people at the hourglass for a special gift!
 
To Enter:
 
* 	Follow @oldthemovie & @mnight on Instagram or Twitter
* 	Take a photo of the hourglass
* 	If you aren’t in LA, head over to @oldthemovie IG story highlights reel to find sweeps rules
* 	Post your photo to Instagram and/or Twitter
* 	Don't forget to include #OldSweepstakes, and mention both @oldthemovie and @mnight in your post!
 
NO PURCHASE NECESSARY. Sweepstakes ends 11:59pm ET on 7/25/21. Subject to Official Rules at:https://uni.pictures/OldSweeps   #universalsponsored

node.text: Every few weeks I feel pressure bubbling up to put on a full face of makeup, try to pose with confidence, and take a new picture for Instagram so all I’m doing is not just posting ads at you. But then I take the pics, feel exhausted, and sit on them for days in the same sweatpants I’ve been in all week. Then eventually pressure bubbles up again and I edit a couple, a process I use to really enjoying doing that now feels like a chore. Then I sit on it for more days despite them being there and ready to post because now I have to write a caption that doesn’t say too much about my life or mind right now because that’d be too much of a downer and no one wants to see that on IG. And it feels incongruous and fake and weird to post anything else and so, for days or weeks I don’t post and just try to sludge through all the offline stuff. Im not sure what to do with this feeling. I feel guilty even sharing it now because I struggle a lot with not wanting to victimize myself while also acknowledging when I’m going through a hard time, but I realized this morning if I didn’t just write the caption that feels accurate, I’ll keep avoiding posting more pics from weeks ago and the cycle will continue. Im not sure how to fake being fully normal when everything about me feels different. Maybe some day I’ll figure it out. For now, if ya have any, tell me a happy story in the comments.

Photo by mykie on June 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Sometimes a very small act of kindness can save someone' s life, and a very small act of unkindness can be their tipping point. Please pass on some kindness today because you don' know who might need it'.

node.text:
Try your best not to participate in something that could be someone’s tipping point. Try your best not to add to someone’s feelings of isolation, unworthiness, or shame, even when you think they “deserve” it. Try to see the humanity in others. You never know what’s truly going on in someone’s life or mind. No one is disposable. Everyone’s life matters.

I fear we’re becoming increasingly numb to this through social media. We are all people reacting, acting and interacting through the lens of our own experiences, insecurities and trauma.  The more hurt you’ve been and the less awake you are to what shapes you, the more pain you’ll cause others, and the more pain you’ll experience yourself. 

This is a lesson I’ve been slowly learning, and one which I wish I had been awake to sooner. I worry about additional pain I may have caused in the past when I was asleep to my own feelings. And we all know what it’s like to be on the receiving end. Now that I understand my own patterns better, I’m beginning to see everyone else’s on full display everywhere I look. 

Our unconscious traumas interact with each other and it’s only when one or more people can step between themselves and their unconscious programming that we make space for compassion, kindness, safety, community and real growth. 

I’m making a committed effort to keep this sentiment in the forefront of my mind.  I have been far from perfect and will continue to fall into my own negative patterns sometimes, but I believe it’s vital to try. I hope anyone who comes across this might consider the same. 

However small the gesture, remind people you care, remind people kindness still exists, remind them they’re not alone. And at the very least, try not to add extra fuel to someone else’s pain. Try to examine where your own pain lies and how you can help alleviate it without negatively effecting others. 

Comments are turned off from the start because I just want to get this out without it feeling like some kind of social currency exchange. If you were going to comment, please use those seconds or that energy to DM someone you care about, or even a stranger.
